observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:
Instruct the MPDC to see to it that succeeding projects of the Municipality are included in the duly approved AIP;
Require the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to promptly return to the BTr the unexpended fund balances from the completed project as of December 31, 2024 amounting to ₱46,621.77 as well as the unexpended balances for projects subsequently completed in the ensuing year in the total amount of ₱26,355.02;
Instruct the Local Finance Committee to prepare the required Report on Fund Utilization and Status of Program/Project Implementation and direct the Municipal Accountant to comply with the necessary posting requirements of the said report and the subsequent notification thereof to the oversight agencies for information purposes and transparency; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to submit the required lacking documents.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:

Submit the JEVs and other supporting documents of those transactions recorded in the Accounts Payable account totaling ₱44,950,309.09 for further evaluation, and thereafter ensure that all transactions recorded under Accounts Payable account are properly documented to achieve faithful representation of all transactions which shall be submitted to the Audit Team;

Prepare the necessary adjusting journal entries relative to the accounts payable found invalid to reflect the correct nature of the said transactions;

Stop the practice of certifying obligations to Accounts Payable that are not founded on valid claims and are not properly supported with sufficient evidence; and 

Ensure that appropriate asset account be recorded only when the items have been received or infrastructure projects have been constructed and accounts payable be recognized when goods have been delivered or services have been rendered.

We reiterated our audit recommendation that Management:

Stop the practice of granting cash advances for operating expenses considering that the LGU has no operating or field units;  

Instruct the Acting Municipal Treasurer to establish PCF for payment of petty or miscellaneous expenses which cannot be conveniently paid through checks, otherwise, issue checks directly payable to the supplier or creditor; 

Determine a reasonable amount of PCF to be set-up based on the needs of the LGU for payment of petty or miscellaneous expenses;

Designate a Special Disbursing Officer (SDO) responsible for the payment of AICS and the allowances of national government officials and its subsequent liquidation; and 

Instruct the Acting Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to strictly comply with the rules and regulations on the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances and use the appropriate accounts based on the nature of cash advances.

We recommended that Management:

Require the Municipal GSO to periodically render the Report on Local Road Networks, and furnish copies to the concerned offices;



Instruct the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the GSO with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;

Require the Municipal Accountant and GSO to maintain separate subsidiary ledgers for each individual road networks and property cards, respectively; and

Direct the Municipal Accountant, GSO and Municipal Engineer to ensure coordination among LGU officials in order to properly implement the accounting and reporting guidelines on the Local Road Asset Management System.

We recommended that Management:

Require the Municipal Accountant and OIC – Municipal Treasurer to stop the practice of granting cash advances for operating expenses considering that the LGU has no operating or field units;  

Instruct the OIC-Municipal Treasurer to establish petty cash fund for payment of petty or miscellaneous expenses which cannot be conveniently paid through checks, otherwise issue checks directly payable to the supplier or creditor; 

Designate a Special Disbursing Officer (SDO) responsible for the payment of the financial assistances and allowances of national government agency officials and its subsequent liquidation thereof; and


Instruct the OIC – Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to strictly comply with the rules and regulations on the grant, utilization and liquidation of the cash advances in conformity with COA Circular No. 97-002 and to use the appropriate accounts based on GAM for LGUs.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Accountant and OIC-Municipal Treasurer to stop the practice of granting cash advances for operating expenses considering that the LGU has no operating or field units;
Instruct the OIC-Municipal Treasurer to establish petty cash fund for payment of petty or miscellaneous expenses which cannot be conveniently paid through checks, otherwise, issue checks directly payable to the supplier or creditor;
Consider to determine a reasonable amount of Petty Cash Fund to be set-up based on the needs of the LGU for payment of petty or miscellaneous expenses;
Designate a Special Disbursing Officer (SDO) responsible for the payment of financial assistance and allowances of national government officials and the subsequent liquidation thereof; and
Instruct the OIC–Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to strictly comply with the rules and regulations on the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances and to use the appropriate accounts based on the nature of cash advances.

The Municipal Accountant and OIC-Municipal Treasurer agreed to comply with the audit recommendations.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal General Services Officer and the Inventory Committee to complete the RPCLRN and submit a copy to the Audit Team for verification;
Instruct the Municipal GSO to periodically render the Report on Local Road Networks, and furnish copy to the Accounting Office;
Require the Municipal GSO to prepare and maintain the Local Road Inventory and Road Map;
Require the Municipal Accountant and Municipal GSO to maintain separate subsidiary ledgers for each individual road networks and local road property cards, respectively;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to disclose the Road Network System in the Notes to the Financial Statement as to the required format; and
Ensure coordination among the concerned LGU offices to properly implement the accounting and reporting guidelines on the Local Road Asset Management System.

The Municipal Accountant and GSO have informed the Audit Team that both have already coordinated for proper implementation of the accounting and reporting guidelines of the Local Road Asset Management System. In addition, reconciliation of their records is already in process.

We recommended that Management instruct the OIC-Municipal Treasurer to:
Regularly update the records on payments of the stallholders;
Strictly impose applicable surcharges as embodied in the Contract of Lease;
Issue Statement of Account at least a month before the rent becomes due, in order to ensure prompt payment of rentals; and
Maximize efforts in collecting delinquent rental fees to generate additional income of the LGU.

The OIC-Municipal Treasurer acknowledged the audit observations and assured compliance with the audit recommendations.

We recommended that Management:

Require the Municipal Accountant and the GSO, in coordination with the BAC, to submit the lacking documents to support the distribution of the donated goods/materials;

Instruct the BAC to prepare and post the RFQs in the PhilGEPS website, website of the Procuring entity, if available, and at any conspicuous place in the premises of the Procuring Entity in compliance with the guidelines on Annex “H” of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184;

Require the Punong Barangays concerned to submit the pertinent reports to support the utilization of the supplies and materials received from the LGU such as, but not limited to Resolutions of the Sangguniang Barangay, AIR, PAR and/or ICS, as applicable; 

Advise all Punong Barangays to prepare and submit all necessary documents from requisition up to receipt of all donations and financial assistance received from the LGU;

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to coordinate with the GSO to submit the proof of receipt or the list duly received by the frontliners on duty at Macarang Checkpoint on the 44 sacks of rice for proper validation; 

Direct the OIC-Municipal Treasurer to submit the payroll or list of recipients duly signed on the distribution of the financial assistance per barangay to support the liquidation of the cash advance amounting to ₱984,000.00 and submit to the Municipal Accountant for further evaluation; 

Instruct the OIC-Municipal Treasurer to see to it that all Official Receipts/Cash Sales Invoice issued by the suppliers/contractors have the correct details including dates and signatures before releasing the payments; and

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to exercise prudence and diligence in his duties and responsibilities as accountable and responsible in the verification of the completeness of the documents for all transactions of the LGU before payments are made.

We recommended that the Management:

Instruct the members of the BAC, BAC Secretariat and Technical Working Group to request for the payment of their honoraria in the year the competitive biddings are conducted to avoid the use of prior years’ unutilized proceeds from the sale of bidding documents;

Require the Municipal Accountant and OIC – Municipal Treasurer to transfer the unutilized proceeds from the sale of bidding documents to the General Fund and consider the amount balances as part of the local funds of the LGU in the budgeting process; 	

Direct the Municipal Accountant to strictly adhere to the salient provisions of DBM Budget Circular No. 2004-5A dated March 23, 2004 and DBM Budget Circular No. 2007-3 dated November 9, 2007 on the computation of honoraria of members of BAC, the TWG and Secretariat to avoid excessive payments; and 

Instruct the BAC Chairman and Municipal Accountant to submit the required lacking documents of the financial transactions.

We recommended that Management:

Require the BAC to update the form used in gathering the lowest calculated and responsive quotation for all transactions involving procurement undertaken through alternative methods to indicate the ABC, and other terms and conditions of the contract;

Instruct the BAC to ensure that the RFQ, as a formal letter from the LGU, is signed by the BAC Chairman;

Direct the BAC to require the suppliers to indicate the brand of goods they are offering and other necessary information that may affect the final evaluation of the offers; and

Require the BAC to prepare the Abstract of Quotations after receiving and evaluating the price quotations and BAC Resolutions Recommending to the HoPE the Award of Contract in favor of the supplier with the Lowest Calculated and Responsive Quotation.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Create an Inventory Committee to conduct the physical count of public infrastructures specially the local road networks; 


Inform the GSO to periodically render Report on Local Road Networks, and furnish copies to the concerned offices;

Require the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;

Require the Municipal Accountant and OIC-Municipal Treasurer to maintain separate subsidiary ledgers for each individual road networks and property cards, respectively; and

Ensure coordination among LGU Offices to properly implement the accounting and reporting guidelines on the Local Road Asset Management System.

We recommended that Management:

Instruct the personnel concerned to regularly conduct Physical Inventory of the Inventory account and reconcile the same with the accounting records and the GSO;

Require the Accounting unit to account for the inventories using the perpetual inventory method and maintain supply ledger cards;

Instruct the GSO to regularly prepare the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) and forward to Accounting Unit to serve as basis in the preparation of JEV and recording of issuances;

Require the GSO to maintain stock cards and record deliveries and issuances therein;

Adhere to the general process in handling and accounting for Inventories and Supplies and Materials prescribed in Manual on the NGAS for LGUs in order to strengthen the internal control of the agency; and

Purchase supplies and materials needed for the quarter based on the approved annual procurement program, at the beginning of the year and of each subsequent quarters thru public bidding pursuant to Republic Act No. 9184 and its IRR.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Require the OIC-Municipal Treasurer to refrain from utilizing Petty Cash Fund for the payment of regular expenses, instead issue checks to the payees concerned as prescribed in COA Circular No. 97-002;

Instruct the OIC-Municipal Treasurer to stop the practice of paying transactions with specific purpose from PCF, instead a cash advance shall be drawn for such purpose;

Require the Municipal Accountant and OIC-Municipal Treasurer to separate the recording and reporting of the cash advances with specific purpose from the petty cash fund; and

Instruct the Petty Cash Custodian to use the Petty Cash Voucher in the disbursement of the fund in conformity with Section 48, Volume I of MNGAS for LGU.

